Week 6 Task 3: JSON Creation
1. Student Information JSON

This JSON structure represents a student’s basic academic details in a system.

{
  "regno": "BIT001",
  "name": "Mary",
  "course": "BIT",
  "year": "3"
}
2. Extended Student Information JSON 

This version includes more realistic system fields used in mobile applications.

{
  "regno": "BIT002",
  "name": "John Kamau",
  "course": "Bachelor of Science in Information Technology",
  "year": "2",
  "email": "john.kamau@example.com",
  "phone": "0712345678",
  "campus": "Main Campus"
}
3. Multiple Students JSON Array 

This shows how multiple records are stored in a system.

[
  {
    "regno": "BIT001",
    "name": "Mary Wanjiku",
    "course": "BIT",
    "year": "3"
  },
  {
    "regno": "BIT002",
    "name": "John Kamau",
    "course": "BIT",
    "year": "2"
  },
  {
    "regno": "BIT003",
    "name": "Amina Ali",
    "course": "BIT",
    "year": "1"
  }
]
Explanation of JSON Structure

JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) is a lightweight data format used to store and exchange data between a client (mobile app) and a server.

Data is stored in key-value pairs
Keys are written in double quotes
Values can be strings, numbers, arrays, or objects
JSON is commonly used in APIs and mobile applications for communication
Conclusion

JSON is an essential part of mobile application development because it allows structured data exchange between applications and servers in a simple and readable format.
